🦞 How Does OpenClaw Work? Inside the Agent Loop That Powers 200,000+ GitHub Stars
20 min read 3 days ago
OpenClaw hit 200,000 GitHub stars in a week. Everyone talks about what it does, but few understand how it actually works. I spent hours reading the source code to find out. The architecture is surprisingly elegant. At its core sits a loop that turns chat messages into executable actions.
This loop runs in src/agents/pi-embedded-runner/run.ts
. Today I'll show you exactly how it works.
Hi, my name is Tom Smykowski, I’m a staff software engineer. I build and scale products to millions of users. On this blog I write about software engineering and AI.
Here’s the core loop, simplified:
while (true) {
const attempt = await runEmbeddedAttempt({
sessionId, sessionKey, prompt, model, tools, ...
});
if (attempt.success) break;
if (attempt.contextOverflow) {
await compactSession();
continue;
}
if (attempt.authError) {
await rotateApiKey();
continue;
}
break; // Other errors exit the loop
}
A loop that keeps trying until it succeeds or hits an unrecoverable error. Everything else builds…
